close_symbols: All return-code definitions used by OS_FileSys_Initialize (error-code enum / header)
explanation:
To determine whether the if-branch in OS_initfs is unreachable you must know what values OS_FileSys_Initialize can actually return and whether the error constants compared in the condition are distinct/possible. Specifically:

- OS_FileSys_Initialize: required to inspect the implementation (or its specification) to see which return codes it can produce so you can tell whether the branch condition can ever be true.

- OS_ERR_INCORRECT_OBJ_STATE and OS_ERR_NO_FREE_IDS: the exact macros/enumeration values are needed to determine if OS_FileSys_Initialize can return these specific codes and to check for accidental aliasing (e.g., both macros equal the same value) which affects reachability.

- OS_FS_ERR_DEVICE_NOT_FREE: needed to confirm the value assigned inside the guarded block (to check for side-effects, possible identical-value replacements, or further simplifications that could make code redundant/unreachable).

- All return-code definitions used by OS_FileSys_Initialize (the error-code enum/header): to see the full set/range of return values and any mappings or translations used inside OS_FileSys_Initialize that influence whether the tested values are possible.

- UT_Stub_RegisterReturnType, UT_Stub_RegisterContextWithMetaData, UT_ExecuteBasicHandler, UT_Stub_GetReturnValuePtr: the static call graph includes the UT stub framework; include these symbols to determine whether test-time stub hooks can force OS_FileSys_Initialize (or the compiled unit) to return arbitrary values. If the project build includes the UT stub machinery that overrides returns, that affects whether the branch is considered reachable in the delivered/project code base or only reachable under test harness instrumentation.

Collecting these symbols (implementation + error-code definitions + test-stub hooks) lets the next analyst decide if the conditional and its body are genuinely unreachable in the project build, or only conditional under test, and therefore whether the code violates the MISRA requirement against unreachable code.
